Presence, not presents, is what leads them to reckless behaviour.
Sense of responsibility
Caregivers affect children, propagate a culture of house-managers raising their youth as norm, fostering parental obscurity and hands-on effect, to mar duties required of youth and sense of responsibility.
A recent study shows: Using the internet for as little as three hours a week increases levels of depression and reduces ‘social support’ (defined as perception that someone is being cared for). If that’s not insane, I don’t know what is!
A note to parents with youth ranging 10-25 years: Social media is raising this digital generation. While reality that children won’t get everything right is comforting, rhetoric remains: Gadgets are here to stay.
Telecommunication gurus, oblivious to fatal dual, caregiving debase role with hitherto referencing side effects to users, continue to expand online empires. This must be addressed. 
Insults hurled at youth to unscramble thorny matters lead to further disengagement for the aggrieved party. Unfortunately, settling scores through violent acts on elderly parents exposes levels of anger, frustration and self-esteem, which grown-ups term “rot in society”.
A study involving content analysis of 142 frequently visited Class of 2008 MySpace profiles found that most 16-17-year-olds displayed health risk behaviours pertaining to substance use, sexual behaviours and violence.



